6 An Act relating to the Roofing Contractor
Registration Act; amending Section 4, Chapter 368,
7 O.S.L. 2025 (59 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 1151.25a),
which relates to residential roofing endorsement;
8 updating statutory references; updating statutory
language; requiring certain continuing education to
9 be determined and approved by the Committee of
Roofing Examiners and the Construction Industries
10 Board; requiring certain valid endorsement to perform
certain work; providing certain exceptions; providing
11 an effective date; and declaring an emergency.
12
13
14 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
15 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY Section 4, Chapter 368, O.S.L.
16 2025 (59 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 1151.25a), is amended to read as
17 follows:
18 Section 1151.25a. A. Except as otherwise provided in the
19 Roofing Contractor Registration Act, on and after the effective date
20 of this act beginning January 1, 2027, every roofing contractor,
21 except for those defined in subsection G of this section, offering
22 to engage in or engaging in performing residential roofing
23 contractor work in this state shall be required to receive a
24 residential roofing endorsement. To receive a residential roofing
ENGR. S. B. NO. 1873 Page 1

1 endo rsement, the roofing contractor shall be required to take and
2 successfully pass a residential roofing examination approved under
3 the provisions of this act the Roofing Contractor Registration Act
4 with a minimum score of seventy percent (70%), and be in compliance
5 with all other provisions of this act the Roofing Contractor
6 Registration Act and rules before acting or being endorsed as a
7 residential roofing contractor. For applicants who have been
8 registered and in good standing with the Construction Industries
9 Board on the effective date of this act on January 1, 2027, there
10 shall be a twelve-month grandfathering-in period from the effective
11 date of this act January 1, 2027, to January 1, 2028, to either pass
12 the exam or complete an additional ten (10) hours of continuing
13 education credits approved in advance by the Committee of Roofing
14 Examiners to be granted a residential roofer endorsement. Any
15 applicant who has been registered, is in good standing with the
16 Board, and possesses a current commercial roofer endorsement on the
17 effective date of this act January 1, 2027, shall be exempt from the
18 residential roofing examination and additional ten (10) hours of
19 continuing education credits required to receive a residential
20 roofing endorsement.
21 B. Examinations for a residential roofer endorsement shall be
22 uniform and practical in nature and sufficiently strict to test the
23 qualifications and fitness of the applicants for endorsement.
24 Examinations shall be in whole or in part in writing. Examinations
ENGR. S. B. NO. 1873 Page 2

1 shal l be offered at least monthly; dates, times, and locations shall
2 be determined by the registrar or third-party vendor with approval
3 of the registrar.
4 C. Any applicant initially failing to pass the examination
5 shall not be permitted to take another examination for a period of
6 thirty (30) days. Any applicant subsequently failing to pass the
7 examination shall not be permitted to take another examination for a
8 period of ninety (90) days. However, in a declared state of
9 emergency, the examination shall be available as often as possible
10 as determined by the registrar.
11 D. No residential roofer endorsement shall be renewed unless
12 the qualifying party has completed the required hours of continuing
13 education pursuant to subsection A of this section, as determined
14 and approved by the Committee of Roofing Examiners.
15 E. For all new applicants not registered and in good standing
16 with the Construction Industries Board on or prior to the effective
17 date of this act January 1, 2027, the Construction Industries Board
18 shall issue a residential roofer endorsement to qualifying
19 applicants no sooner than thirty (30) days from the date of
20 successful completion of the exam. New applicants shall not be
21 allowed to sell, offer, bid, inspect, or perform any residential
22 roofing contractor work in this state until a residential roofer
23 endorsement is issued.
24
ENGR. S. B. NO. 1873 Page 3

1 F. For all applicants registered and in good standing with the
2 Construction Industries Board on or prior to the effective date of
3 this act January 1, 2027:
4 1. The residential roofer endorsement shall be issued
5 immediately upon compliance with the provisions of this section; and
6 2. Applicants shall be allowed to continue residential roofing
7 contractor work at all times during the residential roofer
8 endorsement application process, until January 1, 2028, when all
9 persons shall have a valid residential roofer endorsement to perform
10 residential roofing work unless otherwise exempted under the Roofing
11 Contractor Registration Act.
12 G. The residential roofing endorsement shall not apply to
13 roofing labor contractors who:
14 1. Only provide roofing construction labor services;
15 2. Are working directly for a registered roofing contractor
16 that possesses a residential roofing endorsement; and
17 3. Are not providing any materials.
18 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective July 1, 2026.
19 SECTION 3. It being immediately necessary for the preservation
20 of the public peace, health or safety, an emergency is hereby
21 declared to exist, by reason whereof this act shall take effect and
22 be in full force from and after its passage and approval.
